<!--gc--><div id="abt"><h1><span class="fn">What You Need to Know About Capital Gains</span></h1><h2>How Capital Gains Affect Your Business Taxes</h2><p id="by">By&nbsp;<a href="/bio/Jean-Murray-40292.htm" rel="author">Jean   Murray</a>,&nbsp;About.com Guide</p></div>
<div class="tr"><div class="h4">See More About:</div><ul><li><a href="/lr/filing_business_taxes/1312093/1/" zT="18/1Ys/[1" rel="nofollow">filing business taxes</a></li><li><a href="/lr/shareholders/1312093/2/" zT="18/1Ys/[1" rel="nofollow">shareholders</a></li><li><a href="/lr/owners_equity/1312093/3/" zT="18/1Ys/[1" rel="nofollow">owners equity</a></li></ul></div>
<div id="abm" class="clear"><div id="abc">




<div id="articlebody">
<div id="intro"><p>Capital gains are a mystery to many business owners.&nbsp; You go about your business and let your tax advisor worry about that stuff.&nbsp; But understanding capital gains can help you make better business decisions.&nbsp;</p></div><div class="lsItm"><h2>1. <a href="http://biztaxlaw.about.com/od/glossaryc/g/capitalgain.htm">What are Capital Gains...And Capital Losses?</a></h2><p>How a business incurs capital gains and losses is explained in this article.&nbsp; In addition, you'll learn about the difference between short-term and long-term capital gains/losses and the difference between capital gains/losses and operating profits/losses.</p></div><script>zSB(3,3)</script><div class="lsItm"><h2>2. <a href="http://biztaxlaw.about.com/od/corporations/f/capitalgainsrate.htm">What is the Current Capital Gains Tax Rate?</a></h2><p>The capital gains tax rate differs depending on how long an asset is sold.&nbsp; The capital gains rate for short-term assets (those held one year or less before being sold) is based on the individual income tax rate.&nbsp; The capital gains tax rate for long-term assets is a flat amount.</p></div><div class="lsItm"><h2>3. <a href="http://biztaxlaw.about.com/od/glossarys/g/scheduled.htm">How Do I Report Capital Gains and Capital Losses on My Tax Return?</a></h2><p>First, the IRS says you must report all capital gains on your tax return.&nbsp; This article discusses what happens when you have both capital gains and capital losses during one tax year.</p></div><div class="lsItm"><h2>4. <a href="http://biztaxlaw.about.com/od/capitalgains/f/avoidcapitalgains.htm">More on Capital Gains and Losses from the IRS</a></h2><p>The IRS says you must report all capital gains and only business and investment capital losses can be deducted.&nbsp; The article also discusses what happens if you have both capital gains and capital losses within one tax year.</p></div><div class="lsItm"><h2>5. <a href="http://biztaxlaw.about.com/od/capitalgains/f/capitalgainbizsale.htm">How are Capital Gains and Losses Handled in the Sale of a Business?</a></h2><p>If you are selling your business, the gain or loss on the sale of the assets of the business is considered a capital gain to you as the seller.&nbsp; Read more about how this transaction affects your capital gains tax.</p></div><!--/gc-->
</div>


